# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wavetable-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The timbre of musical instruments can be considered in the light of Fourier theory to consist of multiple harmonic or inharmonic *partials* or overtones.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Each partial is a sine wave of different frequency and amplitude that swells and decays over time due to modulation from an ADSR envelope or low-frequency oscillator.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis most directly generates sound by adding the output of multiple sine wave generators.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Alternative implementations may use pre-computed wavetables or the inverse fast Fourier transform.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The sounds that are heard in everyday life are not characterized by a single frequency.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Instead, they consist of a sum of pure sine frequencies, each one at a different amplitude.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] When humans hear these frequencies simultaneously, we can recognize the sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This is true for both "non-musical" sounds (e.g. water splashing, leaves rustling, etc.) and for "musical sounds" (e.g. a piano note, a bird's tweet, etc.).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This set of parameters (frequencies, their relative amplitudes, and how the relative amplitudes change over time) are encapsulated by the *timbre* of the sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Fourier analysis is the technique that is used to determine these exact timbre parameters from an overall sound signal; conversely, the resulting set of frequencies and amplitudes is called the Fourier series of the original sound signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In the case of a musical note, the lowest frequency of its timbre is designated as the sound's fundamental frequency.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For simplicity, we often say that the note is playing at that fundamental frequency (e.g.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] "middle C is 261.6 Hz"), even though the sound of that note consists of many other frequencies as well.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The set of the remaining frequencies is called the overtones (or the harmonics, if their frequencies are integer multiples of the fundamental frequency) of the sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In other words, the fundamental frequency alone is responsible for the pitch of the note, while the overtones define the timbre of the sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The overtones of a piano playing middle C will be quite different from the overtones of a violin playing the same note; that's what allows us to differentiate the sounds of the two instruments.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] There are even subtle differences in timbre between different versions of the same instrument (for example, an upright piano vs. a grand piano).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis aims to exploit this property of sound in order to construct timbre from the ground up.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By adding together pure frequencies (sine waves) of varying frequencies and amplitudes, we can precisely define the timbre of the sound that we want to create.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Harmonic additive synthesis is closely related to the concept of a Fourier series which is a way of expressing a periodic function as the sum of sinusoidal functions with frequencies equal to integer multiples of a common fundamental frequency.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] These sinusoids are called harmonics, overtones, or generally, partials.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In general, a Fourier series contains an infinite number of sinusoidal components, with no upper limit to the frequency of the sinusoidal functions and includes a DC component (one with frequency of 0 Hz).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Frequencies outside of the human audible range can be omitted in additive synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] As a result, only a finite number of sinusoidal terms with frequencies that lie within the audible range are modeled in additive synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Being inaudible, the DC component, $a_{0}/2$ , and all components with frequencies higher than some finite limit, $Kf_{0}$ , are omitted in the following expressions of additive synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] where $y(t)$ is the synthesis output, $r_{k}$ , $kf_{0}$ , and $\phi _{k}$ are the amplitude, frequency, and the phase offset, respectively, of the k th harmonic partial of a total of K harmonic partials, and $f_{0}$ is the fundamental frequency of the waveform and the frequency of the musical note.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Each envelope $r_{k}(t)\,$ should vary slowly relative to the frequency spacing between adjacent sinusoids.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The bandwidth of $r_{k}(t)$ should be significantly less than $f_{0}$ .
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis can also produce inharmonic sounds (which are aperiodic waveforms) in which the individual overtones need not have frequencies that are integer multiples of some common fundamental frequency.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] While many conventional musical instruments have harmonic partials (e.g. an oboe), some have inharmonic partials (e.g. bells).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] where $f_{k}$ is the constant frequency of k th partial.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In the general case, the instantaneous frequency of a sinusoid is the derivative (with respect to time) of the argument of the sine or cosine function.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] If this frequency is represented in hertz, rather than in angular frequency form, then this derivative is divided by $2\pi$ .
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This is the case whether the partial is harmonic or inharmonic and whether its frequency is constant or time-varying.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Modern-day implementations of additive synthesis are mainly digital.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis can be implemented using a bank of sinusoidal oscillators, one for each partial.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In the case of harmonic, quasi-periodic musical tones, wavetable synthesis can be as general as time-varying additive synthesis, but requires less computation during synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] As a result, an efficient implementation of time-varying additive synthesis of harmonic tones can be accomplished by use of *wavetable synthesis*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Group additive synthesis is a method to group partials into harmonic groups (having different fundamental frequencies) and synthesize each group separately with *wavetable synthesis* before mixing the results.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] An inverse fast Fourier transform can be used to efficiently synthesize frequencies that evenly divide the transform period or "frame".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By careful consideration of the DFT frequency-domain representation it is also possible to efficiently synthesize sinusoids of arbitrary frequencies using a series of overlapping frames and the inverse fast Fourier transform.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It is possible to analyze the frequency components of a recorded sound giving a "sum of sinusoids" representation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This representation can be re-synthesized using additive synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] One method of decomposing a sound into time varying sinusoidal partials is short-time Fourier transform (STFT)-based McAulay-Quatieri Analysis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By modifying the sum of sinusoids representation, timbral alterations can be made prior to resynthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For example, a harmonic sound could be restructured to sound inharmonic, and vice versa.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Sound hybridisation or "morphing" has been implemented by additive resynthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive analysis/resynthesis has been employed in a number of techniques including Sinusoidal Modelling, Spectral Modelling Synthesis (SMS), and the Reassigned Bandwidth-Enhanced Additive Sound Model.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Software that implements additive analysis/resynthesis includes: SPEAR, LEMUR, LORIS, SMSTools, ARSS.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] New England Digital Synclavier had a resynthesis feature where samples could be analyzed and converted into "timbre frames" which were part of its additive synthesis engine.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Technos Acxel, launched in 1987, utilized the additive analysis/resynthesis model, in an FFT implementation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis is used in electronic musical instruments.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It is the principal sound generation technique used by Eminent organs.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In linguistics research, harmonic additive synthesis was used in the 1950s to play back modified and synthetic speech spectrograms.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Later, in the early 1980s, listening tests were carried out on synthetic speech stripped of acoustic cues to assess their significance.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Time-varying formant frequencies and amplitudes derived by linear predictive coding were synthesized additively as pure tone whistles.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This method is called sinewave synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Also the composite sinusoidal modeling (CSM) used on a singing speech synthesis feature on the Yamaha CX5M (1984), is known to use a similar approach which was independently developed during 1966–1979.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] These methods are characterized by extraction and recomposition of a set of significant spectral peaks corresponding to the several resonance modes occurring in the oral cavity and nasal cavity, in a viewpoint of acoustics.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This principle was also utilized on a physical modeling synthesis method, called modal synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Harmonic analysis was discovered by Joseph Fourier, who published an extensive treatise of his research in the context of heat transfer in 1822.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The theory found an early application in prediction of tides.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Around 1876, William Thomson (later ennobled as Lord Kelvin) constructed a mechanical tide predictor.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It consisted of a *harmonic analyzer* and a *harmonic synthesizer*, as they were called already in the 19th century.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The analysis of tide measurements was done using James Thomson's *integrating machine*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The resulting Fourier coefficients were input into the synthesizer, which then used a system of cords and pulleys to generate and sum harmonic sinusoidal partials for prediction of future tides.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In 1910, a similar machine was built for the analysis of periodic waveforms of sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The synthesizer drew a graph of the combination waveform, which was used chiefly for visual validation of the analysis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Georg Ohm applied Fourier's theory to sound in 1843.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The line of work was greatly advanced by Hermann von Helmholtz, who published his eight years worth of research in 1863.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Helmholtz believed that the psychological perception of tone color is subject to learning, while hearing in the sensory sense is purely physiological.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] He supported the idea that perception of sound derives from signals from nerve cells of the basilar membrane and that the elastic appendages of these cells are sympathetically vibrated by pure sinusoidal tones of appropriate frequencies.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Helmholtz agreed with the finding of Ernst Chladni from 1787 that certain sound sources have inharmonic vibration modes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In Helmholtz's time, electronic amplification was unavailable.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For synthesis of tones with harmonic partials, Helmholtz built an electrically excited array of tuning forks and acoustic resonance chambers that allowed adjustment of the amplitudes of the partials.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Built at least as early as in 1862, these were in turn refined by Rudolph Koenig, who demonstrated his own setup in 1872.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For harmonic synthesis, Koenig also built a large apparatus based on his *wave siren*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It was pneumatic and utilized cut-out tonewheels, and was criticized for low purity of its partial tones.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Also tibia pipes of pipe organs have nearly sinusoidal waveforms and can be combined in the manner of additive synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In 1938, with significant new supporting evidence, it was reported on the pages of Popular Science Monthly that the human vocal cords function like a fire siren to produce a harmonic-rich tone, which is then filtered by the vocal tract to produce different vowel tones.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By the time, the additive Hammond organ was already on market.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Most early electronic organ makers thought it too expensive to manufacture the plurality of oscillators required by additive organs, and began instead to build subtractive ones.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In a 1940 Institute of Radio Engineers meeting, the head field engineer of Hammond elaborated on the company's new *Novachord* as having a *"subtractive system"* in contrast to the original Hammond organ in which *"the final tones were built up by combining sound waves"*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Alan Douglas used the qualifiers *additive* and *subtractive* to describe different types of electronic organs in a 1948 paper presented to the Royal Musical Association.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] A typical modern additive synthesizer produces its output as an electrical, analog signal, or as digital audio, such as in the case of software synthesizers, which became popular around year 2000.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The following is a timeline of historically and technologically notable analog and digital synthesizers and devices implementing additive synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In digital implementations of additive synthesis, discrete-time equations are used in place of the continuous-time synthesis equations.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] A notational convention for discrete-time signals uses brackets i.e. $y[n]\,$ and the argument $n\,$ can only be integer values.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] If the continuous-time synthesis output $y(t)\,$ is expected to be sufficiently bandlimited; below half the sampling rate or $f_{\mathrm {s} }/2\,$ , it suffices to directly sample the continuous-time expression to get the discrete synthesis equation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The continuous synthesis output can later be reconstructed from the samples using a digital-to-analog converter.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The velocity of the camera, moving towards the right, constantly increases at the same rate (while to the camera, the objects appear sliding to the left).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Halfway through the 24-second loop, the objects appear to suddenly shift and head in the reverse direction, towards the right.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] In digital signal processing, **aliasing** is a phenomenon in which a reconstructed signal from samples of the original signal contains low frequency components that are not present in the original one.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] This is caused when, in the original signal, there are components at frequency exceeding a certain frequency called Nyquist frequency, ${\textstyle f_{s}/2}$ , where ${\textstyle f_{s}}$ is the sampling frequency (undersampling).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] This is because typical reconstruction methods use low frequency components while there are a number of frequency components, called aliases, which sampling result in the identical sample.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] It also often refers to the distortion or artifact that results when a signal reconstructed from samples is different from the original continuous signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Aliasing can occur in signals sampled in time, for instance in digital audio or the stroboscopic effect, and is referred to as **temporal aliasing**.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Aliasing in spatially sampled signals (e.g., moiré patterns in digital images) is referred to as **spatial aliasing**.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Aliasing is generally avoided by applying low-pass filters or anti-aliasing filters (AAF) to the input signal before sampling and when converting a signal from a higher to a lower sampling rate.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Suitable reconstruction filtering should then be used when restoring the sampled signal to the continuous domain or converting a signal from a lower to a higher sampling rate.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] For spatial anti-aliasing, the types of anti-aliasing include fast approximate anti-aliasing (FXAA), multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA), and supersampling.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Temporal anti-aliasing is a special case of MSAA where pixel samples are collected over multiple frames.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] When a digital image is viewed, a reconstruction is performed by a display or printer device.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] If the image data is processed incorrectly during sampling or reconstruction, the reconstructed image will differ from the original image, and an alias is seen.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] An example of spatial aliasing is the moiré pattern observed in a poorly pixelized image of a brick wall.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Spatial anti-aliasing techniques avoid such poor pixelizations.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Temporal aliasing is a major concern in the sampling of video and audio signals.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Music, for instance, may contain high-frequency components that are outside human's hearing range and hence inaudible.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] If a piece of music is sampled at 32,000 samples per second (Hz), any frequency components at or above 16,000 Hz (the Nyquist frequency for this sampling rate) will cause aliasing when the music is reproduced by a digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The high frequencies in the analog signal will appear as lower frequencies (wrong alias) in the recorded digital sample and, hence, cannot be reproduced by the DAC.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] To prevent this, an anti-aliasing filter is used to remove components above the Nyquist frequency prior to sampling.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] In video or cinematography, temporal aliasing results from the limited frame rate, and causes the wagon-wheel effect, whereby a spoked wheel appears to rotate too slowly or even backwards.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Aliasing has changed its apparent frequency of rotation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] A reversal of direction can be described as a negative frequency.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Temporal aliasing frequencies in video and cinematography are determined by the frame rate of the camera, but the relative intensity of the aliased frequencies is determined by the shutter timing (exposure time) or the use of a temporal aliasing reduction filter during filming.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Like the video camera, most sampling schemes are periodic; that is, they have a characteristic sampling frequency in time or in space.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Digital cameras provide a certain number of samples (pixels) per degree or per radian, or samples per mm in the focal plane of the camera.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Audio signals are sampled (digitized) with an analog-to-digital converter, which produces a constant number of samples per second.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Some of the most dramatic and subtle examples of aliasing occur when the signal being sampled also has periodic content.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Actual signals have a finite duration and their frequency content, as defined by the Fourier transform, has no upper bound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Some amount of aliasing always occurs when such continuous functions over time are sampled.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Functions whose frequency content is bounded (*bandlimited*) have an infinite duration in the time domain.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] If sampled at a high enough rate, determined by the *bandwidth*, the original function can, in theory, be perfectly reconstructed from the infinite set of samples.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Sometimes aliasing is used intentionally on signals with no low-frequency content, called *bandpass* signals.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Undersampling, which creates low-frequency aliases, can produce the same result, with less effort, as frequency-shifting the signal to lower frequencies before sampling at the lower rate.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Some digital channelizers exploit aliasing in this way for computational efficiency.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Sinusoids are an important type of periodic function, because realistic signals are often modeled as the summation of many sinusoids of different frequencies and different amplitudes (for example, with a Fourier series or transform).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Understanding what aliasing does to the individual sinusoids is useful in understanding what happens to their sum.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] A frequency spectrum of the samples produces equally strong responses at all those frequencies.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Without collateral information, the frequency of the original function is ambiguous.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] So, the functions and their frequencies are said to be *aliases* of each other.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] thus, we can write all the alias frequencies as positive values: $f_{_{N}}(f)\triangleq \left|f+Nf_{\rm {s}}\right|$ .
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] For example, a snapshot of the lower right frame of Fig.2 shows a component at the actual frequency f and another component at alias $f_{_{-1}}(f)$ .
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] As f increases during the animation, $f_{_{-1}}(f)$ decreases.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The point at which they are equal $(f=f_{s}/2)$ is an axis of symmetry called the ***folding frequency***, also known as ***Nyquist frequency***.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Aliasing matters when one attempts to reconstruct the original waveform from its samples.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The most common reconstruction technique produces the smallest of the $f_{_{N}}(f)$ frequencies.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] So, it is usually important that $f_{0}(f)$ be the unique minimum.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] A necessary and sufficient condition for that is $f_{s}/2>|f|,$ called the ***Nyquist condition***.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The lower left frame of Fig.2 depicts the typical reconstruction result of the available samples.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Until f exceeds the Nyquist frequency, the reconstruction matches the actual waveform (upper left frame).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] After that, it is the low frequency alias of the upper frame.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The figures below offer additional depictions of aliasing, due to sampling.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] A graph of amplitude vs frequency (not time) for a single sinusoid at frequency 0.6 *f*s and some of its aliases at 0.4 *f*s, 1.4 *f*s, and 1.6 *f*s would look like the 4 black dots in Fig.3.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The red lines depict the paths (loci) of the 4 dots if we were to adjust the frequency and amplitude of the sinusoid along the solid red segment (between *f*s/2 and *f*s).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] No matter what function we choose to change the amplitude vs frequency, the graph will exhibit symmetry between 0 and *f*s.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Folding is often observed in practice when viewing the frequency spectrum of real-valued samples, such as Fig.4.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Complex sinusoids are waveforms whose samples are complex numbers ( ${\textstyle z=Ae^{i\theta }=A(\cos \theta +i\sin \theta )}$ ), and the concept of negative frequency is necessary to distinguish them.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] In that case, the frequencies of the aliases are given by just: *f*N(*f*) = *f* + *N f*s.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] (In real sinusoids, as shown in the above, all alias frequencies can be written as positive frequencies $f_{_{N}}(f)\triangleq \left|f+Nf_{\rm {s}}\right|$ because of sine functions as odd functions.) Therefore, as f increases from 0 to *f*s, *f*−1(*f*) also increases (from –*f*s to 0).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Consequently, complex sinusoids do not exhibit *folding*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] When the condition *f*s/2 > *f* is met for the highest frequency component of the original signal, then it is met for all the frequency components, a condition called the Nyquist criterion.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] That is typically approximated by filtering the original signal to attenuate high frequency components before it is sampled.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] These attenuated high frequency components still generate low-frequency aliases, but typically at low enough amplitudes that they do not cause problems.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] A filter chosen in anticipation of a certain sample frequency is called an anti-aliasing filter.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The filtered signal can subsequently be reconstructed, by interpolation algorithms, without significant additional distortion.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Most sampled signals are not simply stored and reconstructed.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] But the fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction (via the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula) is a customary measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Historically the term *aliasing* evolved from radio engineering because of the action of superheterodyne receivers.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] If it is strong enough it can interfere with reception of the desired signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] This unwanted signal is known as an *image* or *alias* of the desired signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The first written use of the terms "alias" and "aliasing" in signal processing appears to be in a 1949 unpublished Bell Laboratories technical memorandum by John Tukey and Richard Hamming.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] That paper includes an example of frequency aliasing dating back to 1922.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The first *published* use of the term "aliasing" in this context is due to Blackman and Tukey in 1958.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] In their preface to the Dover reprint of this paper, they point out that the idea of aliasing had been illustrated graphically by Stumpf ten years prior.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The 1949 Bell technical report refers to aliasing as though it is a well-known concept, but does not offer a source for the term.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Gwilym Jenkins and Maurice Priestley credit Tukey with introducing it in this context, though an analogous concept of aliasing had been introduced a few years earlier in fractional factorial designs.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] While Tukey did significant work in factorial experiments and was certainly aware of aliasing in fractional designs, it cannot be determined whether his use of "aliasing" in signal processing was consciously inspired by such designs.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Aliasing occurs whenever the use of discrete elements to capture or produce a continuous signal causes frequency ambiguity.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Spatial aliasing, particular of angular frequency, can occur when reproducing a light field or sound field with discrete elements, as in 3D displays or wave field synthesis of sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The lack of parallax on viewer movement in 2D images and in 3-D film produced by stereoscopic glasses (in 3D films the effect is called "yawing", as the image appears to rotate on its axis) can similarly be seen as loss of angular resolution, all angular frequencies being aliased to 0 (constant).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The qualitative effects of aliasing can be heard in the following audio demonstration.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Six sawtooth waves are played in succession, with the first two sawtooths having a fundamental frequency of 440 Hz (A4), the second two having fundamental frequency of 880 Hz (A5), and the final two at 1760 Hz (A6).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The sawtooths alternate between bandlimited (non-aliased) sawtooths and aliased sawtooths and the sampling rate is 22050 Hz.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The bandlimited sawtooths are synthesized from the sawtooth waveform's Fourier series such that no harmonics above the Nyquist frequency (11025 Hz = 22050 Hz / 2 here) are present.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] The aliasing distortion in the lower frequencies is increasingly obvious with higher fundamental frequencies, and while the bandlimited sawtooth is still clear at 1760 Hz, the aliased sawtooth is degraded and harsh with a buzzing audible at frequencies lower than the fundamental.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] A form of spatial aliasing can also occur in antenna arrays or microphone arrays used to estimate the direction of arrival of a wave signal, as in geophysical exploration by seismic waves.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/aliasing] Waves must be sampled more densely than two points per wavelength, or the wave arrival direction becomes ambiguous.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The term *vibration* is precisely used to describe a mechanical oscillation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Oscillation, especially rapid oscillation, may be an undesirable phenomenon in process control and control theory (e.g. in sliding mode control), where the aim is convergence to stable state.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In these cases it is called chattering or flapping, as in valve chatter, and route flapping.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The simplest mechanical oscillating system is a weight attached to a linear spring subject to only weight and tension.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Such a system may be approximated on an air table or ice surface.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The system is in an equilibrium state when the spring is static.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] If the system is displaced from the equilibrium, there is a net *restoring force* on the mass, tending to bring it back to equilibrium.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] However, in moving the mass back to the equilibrium position, it has acquired momentum which keeps it moving beyond that position, establishing a new restoring force in the opposite sense.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] If a constant force such as gravity is added to the system, the point of equilibrium is shifted.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The time taken for an oscillation to occur is often referred to as the oscillatory *period*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The systems where the restoring force on a body is directly proportional to its displacement, such as the dynamics of the spring-mass system, are described mathematically by the simple harmonic oscillator and the regular periodic motion is known as simple harmonic motion.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In the spring-mass system, oscillations occur because, at the static equilibrium displacement, the mass has kinetic energy which is converted into potential energy stored in the spring at the extremes of its path.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The spring-mass system illustrates some common features of oscillation, namely the existence of an equilibrium and the presence of a restoring force which grows stronger the further the system deviates from equilibrium.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] where ω is the frequency of the oscillation, A is the amplitude, and δ is the phase shift of the function.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] These are determined by the initial conditions of the system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Because cosine oscillates between 1 and −1 infinitely, our spring-mass system would oscillate between the positive and negative amplitude forever without friction.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In two or three dimensions, harmonic oscillators behave similarly to one dimension.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] With anisotropic oscillators, different directions have different constants of restoring forces.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The solution is similar to isotropic oscillators, but there is a different frequency in each direction.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Varying the frequencies relative to each other can produce interesting results.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] For example, if the frequency in one direction is twice that of another, a figure eight pattern is produced.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] If the ratio of frequencies is irrational, the motion is quasiperiodic.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This motion is periodic on each axis, but is not periodic with respect to r, and will never repeat.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] All real-world oscillator systems are thermodynamically irreversible.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This means there are dissipative processes such as friction or electrical resistance which continually convert some of the energy stored in the oscillator into heat in the environment.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Thus, oscillations tend to decay with time unless there is some net source of energy into the system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The simplest description of this decay process can be illustrated by oscillation decay of the harmonic oscillator.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Damped oscillators are created when a resistive force is introduced, which is dependent on the first derivative of the position, or in this case velocity.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The differential equation created by Newton's second law adds in this resistive force with an arbitrary constant b.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The exponential term outside of the parenthesis is the decay function and β is the damping coefficient.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] There are 3 categories of damped oscillators: under-damped, where *β* < *ω*0; over-damped, where *β* > *ω*0; and critically damped, where *β* = *ω*0.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In addition, an oscillating system may be subject to some external force, as when an AC circuit is connected to an outside power source.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In this case the oscillation is said to be *driven*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The second term of *x*(*t*) is the transient solution to the differential equation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The transient solution can be found by using the initial conditions of the system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Some systems can be excited by energy transfer from the environment.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This transfer typically occurs where systems are embedded in some fluid flow.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] At sufficiently large displacements, the stiffness of the wing dominates to provide the restoring force that enables an oscillation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Resonance occurs in a damped driven oscillator when ω = ω0, that is, when the driving frequency is equal to the natural frequency of the system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] When this occurs, the denominator of the amplitude is minimized, which maximizes the amplitude of the oscillations.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The harmonic oscillator and the systems it models have a single degree of freedom.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] More complicated systems have more degrees of freedom, for example, two masses and three springs (each mass being attached to fixed points and to each other).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In such cases, the behavior of each variable influences that of the others.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This leads to a *coupling* of the oscillations of the individual degrees of freedom.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] For example, two pendulum clocks (of identical frequency) mounted on a common wall will tend to synchronise.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This phenomenon was first observed by Christiaan Huygens in 1665.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The apparent motions of the compound oscillations typically appears very complicated but a more economic, computationally simpler and conceptually deeper description is given by resolving the motion into normal modes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The simplest form of coupled oscillators is a 3 spring, 2 mass system, where masses and spring constants are the same.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Depending on the starting point of the masses, this system has 2 possible frequencies (or a combination of the two).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] If the masses are started with their displacements in the same direction, the frequency is that of a single mass system, because the middle spring is never extended.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] If the two masses are started in opposite directions, the second, faster frequency is the frequency of the system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] More special cases are the coupled oscillators where energy alternates between two forms of oscillation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Well-known is the Wilberforce pendulum, where the oscillation alternates between the elongation of a vertical spring and the rotation of an object at the end of that spring.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Coupled oscillators are a common description of two related, but different phenomena.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] One case is where both oscillations affect each other mutually, which usually leads to the occurrence of a single, entrained oscillation state, where both oscillate with a *compromise frequency*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Another case is where one external oscillation affects an internal oscillation, but is not affected by this.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In this case the regions of synchronization, known as Arnold Tongues, can lead to highly complex phenomena as for instance chaotic dynamics.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] In physics, a system with a set of conservative forces and an equilibrium point can be approximated as a harmonic oscillator near equilibrium.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The system will undergo oscillations near the equilibrium point.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This approximation can be better understood by looking at the potential curve of the system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] By thinking of the potential curve as a hill, in which, if one placed a ball anywhere on the curve, the ball would roll down with the slope of the potential curve.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] By thinking of the potential in this way, one will see that at any local minimum there is a "well" in which the ball would roll back and forth (oscillate) between $r_{\text{min}}$ and $r_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] This approximation is also useful for thinking of Kepler orbits.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] As the number of degrees of freedom becomes arbitrarily large, a system approaches continuity; examples include a string or the surface of a body of water.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] Such systems have (in the classical limit) an infinite number of normal modes and their oscillations occur in the form of waves that can characteristically propagate.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] The mathematics of oscillation deals with the quantification of the amount that a sequence or function tends to move between extremes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/oscillator] There are several related notions: oscillation of a sequence of real numbers, oscillation of a real-valued function at a point, and oscillation of a function on an interval (or open set).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A **synthesizer** (also **synthesiser** or **synth**) is an electronic musical instrument that generates audio signals.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers typically create sounds by generating waveforms through methods including subtractive synthesis, additive synthesis, and frequency modulation synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] These sounds may be altered by components such as filters, which cut or boost frequencies; envelopes, which control articulation, or how notes begin and end; and low-frequency oscillators, which modulate parameters such as pitch, volume, or filter characteristics affecting timbre.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are typically played with keyboards or controlled by sequencers, software or other instruments, and can be synchronized to other equipment via MIDI.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer-like instruments emerged in the United States in the mid-20th century with instruments such as the RCA Mark II, which was controlled with punch cards and used hundreds of vacuum tubes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog synthesizer, developed by Robert Moog and first sold in 1964, is credited for pioneering concepts such as voltage-controlled oscillators, envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, the smaller, cheaper Minimoog standardized synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards, unlike the larger modular synthesizers before it.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, which used microprocessors to allow users to store sounds for the first time.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments, was introduced in 1982 and remains an industry standard.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, launched in 1983, was a major success and popularized digital synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Software synthesizers now can be run as plug-ins or embedded on microchips.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 21st century, analog synthesizers returned to popularity with the advent of cheaper manufacturing.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were initially viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and countercultural scenes but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968)*,* a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, took synthesizers to the mainstream.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They were adopted by electronic acts and pop and rock groups in the 1960s and 1970s and were widely used in 1980s music.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced genres such as electronic and hip hop music.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is used in nearly every genre and is considered one of the most important instruments in the music industry.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] As electricity became more widely available, the early 20th century saw the invention of electronic musical instruments including the Telharmonium, Trautonium, ondes Martenot and theremin.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1930s, the Hammond Organ Company built the Novachord, a large instrument powered by 72 voltage-controlled amplifiers and 146 vacuum tubes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1948, the Canadian engineer Hugh Le Caine completed the electronic sackbut, a precursor to voltage-controlled synthesizers, with keyboard sensitivity allowing for vibrato, glissando, and attack control.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1957, Harry Olson and Herbert Belar completed the RCA Mark II Sound Synthesizer at the RCA laboratories in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The instrument read punched paper tape that controlled an analog synthesizer containing 750 vacuum tubes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was acquired by the Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center and used almost exclusively by Milton Babbitt, a composer at Princeton University.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* define "the early years of the synthesizer" as between 1964 and the mid-1970s, beginning with the debut of the Moog synthesizer, designed by the American engineer Robert Moog.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was composed of separate modules connected by patch cables that generate, shape or control sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog developed a means of controlling pitch through voltage, the voltage-controlled oscillator.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This, along with Moog components such as envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers, became standard components in synthesizers.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Around the same period, the American engineer Don Buchla created the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Instead of a conventional keyboard, Buchla's system used touchplates which transmitted control voltages depending on finger position and force.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, the Moog's keyboard made it more accessible and marketable to musicians, and keyboards became the standard means of controlling synthesizers.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog and Buchla initially avoided the word *synthesizer* for their instruments, as it was associated with the RCA synthesizer; however, by the 1970s, it had become the standard term.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, Moog launched a cheaper, smaller synthesizer, the Minimoog.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was the first synthesizer sold in music stores, and was more practical for live performance.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It standardized the concept of synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the early 1970s, the British composer Ken Freeman introduced the first string synthesizer, designed to emulate string sections.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] After retail stores started selling synthesizers in 1971, other synthesizer companies were established, including ARP in the US and EMS in the UK.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP's products included the ARP 2600, which folded into a carrying case and had built-in speakers, and the Odyssey, a rival to the Minimoog.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The less expensive EMS synthesizers were used by European art rock and progressive rock acts including Brian Eno and Pink Floyd.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Designs for synthesizers appeared in the amateur electronics market, such as a design published in *Practical Electronics* in 1973.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] By the mid-1970s, ARP was the world's largest synthesizer manufacturer, though it closed in 1981.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were monophonic, meaning they could only play one note at a time.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Some of the earliest commercial polyphonic synthesizers were created by the American engineer Tom Oberheim, such as the OB-X (1979).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, the American company Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, the first fully programmable polyphonic synthesizer.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Whereas previous synthesizers required users to adjust cables and knobs to change sounds, with no guarantee of exactly recreating a sound, the Prophet-5 used microprocessors to store sounds in patch memory.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This facilitated a move from synthesizers creating unpredictable sounds to producing "a standard package of familiar sounds".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The synthesizer market grew dramatically in the 1980s.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] 1982 saw the introduction of MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments; it remains an industry standard.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] An influential sampling synthesizer, the Fairlight CMI, was released in 1979, with the ability to record and play back samples at different pitches.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Though its high price made it inaccessible to amateurs, it was adopted by high-profile pop musicians including Kate Bush and Peter Gabriel.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The success of the Fairlight drove competition, improving sampling technology and lowering prices.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early competing samplers included the E-mu Emulator in 1981 and the Akai S-series in 1985.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1983, Yamaha released the first commercially successful digital synthesizer, the Yamaha DX7.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Based on frequency modulation (FM) synthesis developed by the Stanford University engineer John Chowning, the DX7 was characterized by its *harsh*, *glassy* and *chilly* sounds, compared to the *warm* and *fuzzy* sounds of analog synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 unitsand remains one of the bestselling in history.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Digital synthesizers typically contained preset sounds emulating acoustic instruments, with algorithms controlled with menus and buttons.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Synclavier, made with FM technology licensed from Yamaha, offered features such as 16-bit sampling and digital recording.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With a starting price of $13,000, its use was limited to universities, studios and wealthy artists.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Roland D-50 (1987) blended Roland's linear arithmetic algorithm with samples, and was the first mass-produced synthesizer with built-in digital effects such as delay, reverb and chorus.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1988, the Japanese manufacturer Korg released the M1, a digital synthesizer workstation featuring sampled transients and loops.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With more than 250,000 units sold, it remains the bestselling synthesizer in history.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The advent of digital synthesizers led to a downturn in interest in analog synthesizers in the following decade.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ReBirth by Propellerhead Software and Reality by Seer Systems, the first software synthesizers that could be played in real time via MIDI, were released in 1997.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1999, an update to the music software Cubase allowed users to run software instruments (including synthesizers) as plug-ins, triggering a wave of new software instruments.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Propellerhead's Reason, released in 2000, introduced an array of recognizable virtual studio equipment.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The market for patchable and modular synthesizers rebounded in the late 1990s.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2000s, older analog synthesizers regained popularity, sometimes selling for much more than their original prices.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2010s, new, affordable analog synthesizers were introduced by companies including Moog, Korg, Arturia and Dave Smith Instruments.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The renewed interest is credited to the appeal of imperfect *organic* sounds and simpler interfaces, and modern surface-mount technology making analog synthesizers cheaper and faster to manufacture.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and counter-cultural scenes for their ability to make new sounds, but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968), a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, demonstrated that synthesizers could be more than "random noise machines", taking them to the mainstream.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, debates were held about the appropriateness of synthesizers in baroque music, and according to the *Guardian* they were quickly abandoned in "serious classical circles".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is one of the most important instruments in the music industry, used in nearly every genre.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It is considered by the authors of *Analog Days* as "the only innovation that can stand alongside the electric guitar as a great new instrument of the age of electricity ...
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was adopted by 1960s rock acts including the Doors, the Grateful Dead, the Rolling Stones, the Beatles, and Keith Emerson.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Emerson was the first major rock musician to perform with the Moog and it became a trademark of his performances, helping take his band Emerson, Lake & Palmer to global stardom.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] According to *Analog Days*, the likes of Emerson, with his Moog performances, "did for the keyboard what Jimi Hendrix did for the guitar".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] String synthesizers were used by 1970s progressive rock bands including Camel, Caravan, Electric Light Orchestra, Gentle Giant and Renaissance.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The portable Minimoog (1970), much smaller than the modular synthesizers before it, made synthesizers more common in live performance.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers could only play one note at a time, making them suitable for basslines, leads and solos.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With the rise of polyphonic synthesizers in the 1970s and 1980s, "the keyboard in rock once more started to revert to the background, to be used for fills and atmosphere rather than for soloing".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Queen included statements in their 1970s album notes specifying that no synthesisers had been used, but added them in their 1980 album *The Game*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Minimoog took a place in mainstream African-American music, most notably in the work of Stevie Wonder, and in jazz, such as the work of Sun Ra.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1970s and the early 1980s, the Minimoog was widely used in the emerging disco genre by artists including Abba and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced all genres of music and had a major influence on the development of electronic and hip hop music.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s, electronic music composers such as Jean Michel Jarre and Isao Tomita released successful synthesizer-led instrumental albums.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This influenced the emergence of synth-pop from the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The sequencer-based Roland TB-303 (1981), in conjunction with the Roland TR-808 and TR-909 drum machines, became a foundation of electronic dance music genres such as house and techno when producers acquired cheap second-hand units later in the decade.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* connect the synthesizer's origins in 1960s psychedelia to the raves and British Second Summer of Love of the 1980s and the club scenes of the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Gary Numan's 1979 hits "Are 'Friends' Electric?" and "Cars" made heavy use of synthesizers.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] OMD's "Enola Gay" (1980) used distinctive electronic percussion and a synthesized melody.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Soft Cell used a synthesized melody on their 1981 hit "Tainted Love".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Nick Rhodes, the keyboardist of Duran Duran, used synthesizers including the Roland Jupiter-4 and Jupiter-8.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Chart hits include Depeche Mode's "Just Can't Get Enough" (1981), the Human League's "Don't You Want Me" and works by Ultravox.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, digital synthesizers were widely used in pop music.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, released in 1983, became a pop staple, used on songs by A-ha, Kenny Loggins, Kool & the Gang.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Its E PIANO 1 preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads, and was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Prince, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, and Celine Dion.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Korg M1 presets were widely used in 1990s house music, beginning with Madonna's 1990 single "Vogue".
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are common in film and television soundtracks.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1969, Mort Garson used a Moog to compose a soundtrack for the televised footage of the Apollo 11 moonwalk, creating a link between electronic music and space in the American popular imagination.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP synthesizers were used to create sound effects for the 1977 science fiction films *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* and *Star Wars*, including the voice of the robot R2-D2.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s and 1980s, synthesizers were used in the scores for thrillers and horror films including *A Clockwork Orange* (1971), *Apocalypse Now* (1979), *The Fog* (1980) and *Manhunter* (1986).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Brad Fiedel used a Prophet synthesizer to record the soundtrack for *The Terminator* (1984), and the filmmaker John Carpenter used them extensively for his soundtracks.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were used to create themes for television shows including *Knight Rider* (1982)*, Twin Peaks* (1990) and *Stranger Things* (2016).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The rise of the synthesizer led to major changes in the music industry, including job displacement, comparable to the 1920s arrival of sound in film, which put live musicians accompanying silent films out of work.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With its ability to imitate instruments such as strings and horns, the synthesizer threatened the jobs of session musicians by allowing one keyboardist or music programmer to produce the same range of sounds as an entire orchestra.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] For a period, the Moog was banned from use in union work, a restriction negotiated by the American Federation of Musicians (AFM).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The musician Walter Sear persuaded the AFM that the synthesizer demanded skill, and the category of *synthesizer player* was accepted into the union.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, players were subject to "suspicion and hostility" for years.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1982, following a tour by Barry Manilow using synthesizers instead of an orchestra, the British Musicians' Union attempted to ban synthesizers, attracting controversy.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, a few musicians skilled at programming the Yamaha DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers generate audio through various forms of analog and digital synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Oscillators produce waveforms (such as sawtooth, sine, or pulse waves) with different timbres.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Voltage-controlled amplifiers (VCAs) control the volume or gain of the audio signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] VCAs can be modulated by other components, such as LFOs and envelopes.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A VCA is a preamp that boosts (amplifies) the electronic signal before passing it on to an external or built-in power amplifier, as well as a means to control its amplitude (volume) using an attenuator.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The gain of the VCA is affected by a *control voltage* (CV), coming from an envelope generator, an LFO, the keyboard or some other source.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Envelopes control how sounds change over time.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They may control parameters such as amplitude (volume), filters (frequencies), or pitch.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Low-frequency oscillators (LFOs) produce waveforms used to modulate parameters, such as the pitch of oscillators (producing vibrato).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters remove frequencies from the audio signal, similarly to equalization, to shape sounds.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They typically include controls to set the point at which frequencies are attenuated, and to add resonance.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Common types include low-pass filters, which remove audio above a specified frequency, and high-pass filters, which do the opposite.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters may be controlled with envelopes or LFOs.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Arpeggiators take input chords and convert them into arpeggios.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They usually include controls for speed, range and mode (the movement of the arpeggio).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are often controlled with electronic or digital keyboards or MIDI controller keyboards, which may be built into the synthesizer unit or attached via connections such as CV/gate, USB, or MIDI.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Keyboards may offer expression such as velocity sensitivity and aftertouch, allowing for more control over the sound.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer clones are unlicensed recreations of previous synthesizers, often marketed as affordable versions of famous musical equipment.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Clones are available as physical instruments and software.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Companies that have sold software clones include Arturia and Native Instruments.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Behringer manufactures equipment modelled on instruments including the Minimoog, Pro-One, and TB-303, and drum machines such as the TR-808.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Other synthesizer clones include the MiniMOD (a series of Eurorack modules based on the Minimoog), the Intellijel Atlantis (based on the SH-101), and the x0x Heart (based on the TB-303).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Creating clones of older hardware is legal where the patents have expired.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1997, Mackie lost their lawsuit against Behringer as copyright law in the United States did not cover their circuit board designs.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] To produce output, the system selects a starting point within the table and a length, and the system loops through that section of the stored waveforms and plays it repeatedly.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Each amplitude value is read from memory in turn, often stored in ROM.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] The series of numbers being read is sent into an digital-to-analog converter, which converts the value into an electrical signal to produce an audible signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Most systems include the capability to mix multiple samples together to produce more complex output.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] One example of the technique is in the Waldorf Microwave synthesizer which had loadable wavetables.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] One consisted of the statement "nineteen twenty" from a voice synthesizer.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] By selecting different starting points and lengths within this sample, a wide variety of sounds can be produced.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Wavetable synthesis was invented by Max Mathews in 1958 as part of MUSIC II.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Hal Chamberlin discussed wavetable synthesis in Byte's September 1977 issue.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Wolfgang Palm of Palm Products GmbH (PPG) developed his version in the late 1970s and published it in 1979.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] The technique has since been used as the primary synthesis method in synthesizers built by PPG and Waldorf Music and as an auxiliary synthesis method by Ensoniq and Access.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] It is currently used in hardware synthesizers from Waldorf Music and in software synthesizers for PCs and tablets, including apps offered by PPG and Waldorf, among others.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] It was also independently developed by Michael McNabb, who used it in his 1978 composition *Dreamsong*.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Electronic synthesizers using digital techniques generally produce sounds by producing a digital value, a number, and then sending that value to an digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that produces a scaled output voltage.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] For instance, to produce a triangle wave or sawtooth, systems used a register containing a starting value, normally zero, and then periodically increase or decrease the value using an adder or phase accumulator.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] The value in the register is continually sent to the DAC to produce output.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] The pitch of the resulting sound can be changed by how rapidly the adder is called.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Wavetable synthesis is a relatively simple modification of this sort of system.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Instead of the value at any particular instantly being periodically modified by a simple function like addition, the specific value for any instant is read from memory containing a series of values making up multiple arbitrary, single-cycle waveforms.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] This allows the waveform to have any shape, not just simple ones like triangles or sines.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] With that exception, the system is otherwise the same; values are read into the register at a rate that produces the desired pitch, and the output of the register is used to feed a DAC that produces the output signal.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] In order to produce a different sound, all that has to be changed is a single value pointing to the starting point of the waveform in memory.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Because the table contains many different waveforms, playing a longer sample that includes several different waveforms may result in odd side-effects when the system crosses the boundaries between the individual waveforms.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Digital interpolation between adjacent waveforms allows for dynamic and smooth changes of the timbre of the tone produced.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Additional effects can be provided by reading the waveform forward or backward, and further controlled in a number of ways, for example, by use of an LFO, envelope, pressure or velocity.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Many wavetables used in PPG and Ensoniq synthesizers can simulate the methods used by analog synthesizers, such as pulse-width modulation by utilising a number of square waves of different duty cycles.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] In this way, when the wavetable is swept, the duty cycle of the pulse wave will appear to change over time.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] As the early Ensoniq wavetable synthesizers had non resonant filters (the PPG Wave synthesizers used Curtis analogue resonant filters), some wavetables contained highly resonant waveforms to overcome this limitation of the filters.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] In 1992, with the introduction of the Creative Labs Sound Blaster 16 the term "wavetable" started to be (incorrectly) applied as a marketing term to their sound card.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] However, these sound cards did not employ any form of wavetable synthesis, but rather PCM samples and FM synthesis.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] The creation of new wavetables was previously a difficult process unless supported by specialized editing facilities and (near) real-time playback of edited wavetables on the synthesizer.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Such editors often required the use of extra hardware devices like the PPG Waveterm or were only present in expensive models like the Waldorf WAVE.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] More commonly, pre-computed wavetables could be added via memory cards or sent to the synthesizer via MIDI.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Today, wavetables can be created more easily by software and auditioned directly on a computer.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Since all waveforms used in wavetable synthesis are periodic, the time-domain and frequency-domain representation are exact equivalents of each other and both can be used simultaneously to define waveforms and wavetables.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] During playback, the sound produced can be harmonically changed by moving to another point in the wavetable, usually under the control of an envelope generator or low-frequency oscillator but frequently by any number of modulators (matrix modulation).
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] Doing this modifies the harmonic content of the output wave in real time, producing sounds that can imitate acoustic instruments or be totally abstract, which is where this method of sound creation excels.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] The technique is especially useful for evolving synth pads, where the sound changes slowly over time.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] It is often necessary to 'audition' each position in a wavetable and to scan through it, forwards and backwards, in order to make good use of it, though selecting random wavetables, start positions, end positions and directions of scan can also produce satisfying musical results.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] It is worth noting that most wavetable synthesizers also employ other synthesis methods to further shape the output waveform, such as subtractive synthesis (filters), phase modulation, frequency modulation and AM (ring) modulation.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] , where the data at addresses from 63 to 67 are zoomed.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] On Csound, it is called *f-table* (function table), and used for various purposes including: wavetable-lookup synthesis, waveshaping, MIDI note mapping, and storing ordered pitch-class sets.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] However, the derived term "*wavetable synthesis*" seems slightly confused by the later developments of derived algorithm.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] In the mid-2000s, confusion in terminology cropped up yet-again.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] A subclass of generic wavetable synthesis, *i.e.* McNabb and Palm's multiple wavetable synthesis, tends to be erroneously referred as if it was a generic class of whole wavetable synthesis family, exclusively.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] As a result, the difficulty of maintaining consistency between concepts and terminology during rapid technological development is noteworthy.
[src:wavetable-synthesis/table-lookup-synthesis] For this reason the term "Table-lookup synthesis" is explained at length in this article.
